      "<b>Part 1: Introduction to Information Identification</b>:<br><br>Objective: Understand the importance of identifying different types of information from various subjects.<br><br>Information can be found in many forms, such as books, newspapers, the internet, and through people’s experiences.<br><br>Identifying information means recognizing facts, ideas, and knowledge that are relevant to a particular topic, like history, current affairs, or personal experiences.<br><br>Examples:<br>Identifying information about agriculture: What crops are grown in different regions? Which countries are known for specific agricultural products?<br>Identifying information about democracy: What is the meaning of democracy? Who are the leaders in a democratic government?",
      "<b>Part 2: Classification of Information</b>:<br><br>Objective: Learn how to classify information into categories based on its nature or subject.<br><br>Classification means grouping information based on similarities, such as classifying countries based on their geography or economy, or classifying people based on their customs or laws.<br><br>Topics to classify information include:<br>Countries (e.g., by continent or economy)<br>People (e.g., by culture or traditions)<br>Customs and Laws (e.g., by country or region)<br>Agriculture (e.g., by type of crops grown)<br>Current Affairs and Issues (e.g., topics like HIV and AIDS, gender, governance, etc.)<br><br>Examples:<br>Countries: Classifying countries by their level of development or geography (e.g., Africa, Asia, North America).<br>HIV and AIDS: Understanding different viewpoints, statistics, and prevention methods in various countries.",
      "<b>Part 3: Using Information</b>:<br><br>Objective: Understand how to use identified and classified information in decision-making and everyday life.<br><br>Using information means applying knowledge in real situations, like solving problems, making decisions, or understanding the world better.<br><br>Information can help us make informed decisions on various issues such as governance, conservation, or healthcare.<br><br>Examples:<br>Using information about democracy: If you know how democracy works, you can make better choices during elections.<br>Using information about agriculture: If you know what crops grow best in certain climates, you can support farmers with better knowledge on how to improve their yields.",
